WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.750 --> 00:00:06.200
ROBIN ROSENBERG: Thank you.

00:00:06.200 --> 00:00:09.490
My talk today is "Superheroes
and the Life Lessons They

00:00:09.490 --> 00:00:13.870
Teach Us." And part of my
mission is that I think the

00:00:13.870 --> 00:00:17.857
scientific psychology, we know a
lot of fun facts to know and

00:00:17.857 --> 00:00:21.110
tell that can more importantly
improve people's lives

00:00:21.110 --> 00:00:22.090
if only they knew.

00:00:22.090 --> 00:00:23.615
And even if they knew,
the important thing

00:00:23.615 --> 00:00:24.890
is that they remember.

00:00:24.890 --> 00:00:29.430
So what I try to do is teach
these little kernels in ways

00:00:29.430 --> 00:00:30.170
that are memorable.

00:00:30.170 --> 00:00:33.020
And popular culture figures
are great examples.

00:00:33.020 --> 00:00:36.020
Superheroes, in particular,
are wonderful examples.

00:00:36.020 --> 00:00:38.040
Let me tell you a little bit
about how I got started on

00:00:38.040 --> 00:00:42.840
this venture, in this
trajectory, if you will.

00:00:42.840 --> 00:00:45.410
I have three sons.

00:00:45.410 --> 00:00:50.710
And when the oldest two were in
preschool, they came home

00:00:50.710 --> 00:00:51.950
talking about the X-Men.

00:00:51.950 --> 00:00:53.680
So I read comics as a kid.

00:00:53.680 --> 00:00:55.620
Mostly DC, I have to admit.

00:00:55.620 --> 00:01:00.140
And the X-Men was after
my time as a kid.

00:01:00.140 --> 00:01:04.129
And so they were coming home
wanting to know about X-Men,

00:01:04.129 --> 00:01:06.760
or wanting to watch Saturday
morning cartoons and talking

00:01:06.760 --> 00:01:07.330
about X-Men.

00:01:07.330 --> 00:01:09.690
And so I bought some
X-Men cartoons,

00:01:09.690 --> 00:01:11.750
comic books, and videos.

00:01:11.750 --> 00:01:14.380
And I was also writing an
introductory psychology

00:01:14.380 --> 00:01:16.410
textbook at the time for
college students.

00:01:16.410 --> 00:01:20.760
And I opened up the X-Men
comics, and I was blown away

00:01:20.760 --> 00:01:22.390
by how much psychology
there was.

00:01:22.390 --> 00:01:25.480
Show of hands, how many people
are familiar with X-Men?

00:01:25.480 --> 00:01:27.420
OK, good.

00:01:27.420 --> 00:01:30.300
And so that started
me on this path.

00:01:30.300 --> 00:01:33.210
So I'll be using a lot
of examples as

00:01:33.210 --> 00:01:34.500
you'll be able to see.

00:01:34.500 --> 00:01:37.470
I'm going to talk about
hopefully four, but

00:01:37.470 --> 00:01:39.920
realistically probably
three lessons.

00:01:39.920 --> 00:01:42.450
One is being different
can give you power.

00:01:42.450 --> 00:01:44.970
Another is adversity
can be overcome.

00:01:44.970 --> 00:01:46.150
And the costume counts.

00:01:46.150 --> 00:01:47.400
My mother was right.

00:01:49.840 --> 00:01:52.200
And then if we have time, I'll
do superheroes aren't the only

00:01:52.200 --> 00:01:53.930
ones with alter-egos.

00:01:53.930 --> 00:01:56.040
OK, so being different
can give you power.

00:01:56.040 --> 00:01:58.100
Show of hands, how
many people here

00:01:58.100 --> 00:02:01.600
grew up feeling different?

00:02:01.600 --> 00:02:05.300
How many people grew up
not feeling different?

00:02:05.300 --> 00:02:06.220
Wow.

00:02:06.220 --> 00:02:08.180
OK, so one person raised
their hand.

00:02:08.180 --> 00:02:09.039
It's unusual.

00:02:09.039 --> 00:02:11.009
Usually everybody raises
their hand.

00:02:11.009 --> 00:02:12.315
So we can talk more
afterwards.

00:02:15.960 --> 00:02:19.490
There is a phenomenon in
psychology where human beings

00:02:19.490 --> 00:02:24.150
are wired with something called
social categorization.

00:02:24.150 --> 00:02:27.640
We're prone to divide the world
into "us" versus "them."

00:02:27.640 --> 00:02:32.700
And we are always in "us,"
wherever we are.

00:02:32.700 --> 00:02:35.520
"Them," the technical
term is outgroup.

00:02:35.520 --> 00:02:38.240
And those people are generally
considered more negatively.

00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:40.590
They have more undesirable
attributes.

00:02:40.590 --> 00:02:44.860
And outgroup is seen as more
homogeneous than it really is.

00:02:44.860 --> 00:02:48.110
So, for instance, vampires,
unless there's something I

00:02:48.110 --> 00:02:50.690
don't know going on,
are the outgroup.

00:02:50.690 --> 00:02:53.540
And so we view them as
pretty similar--

00:02:53.540 --> 00:02:55.870
fangs, suck blood, that
kind of thing.

00:02:55.870 --> 00:02:59.195
And we don't generally like
them, at least until recently.

00:03:01.930 --> 00:03:03.850
And that's another example
of an outgroup.

00:03:03.850 --> 00:03:07.140
That's the 1966 "Batman"
villains.

00:03:07.140 --> 00:03:08.330
I mean, they're very colorful.

00:03:08.330 --> 00:03:11.380
But we it's all "them."

00:03:11.380 --> 00:03:13.710
"Us," the term is the ingroup.

00:03:13.710 --> 00:03:16.880
And we consider ourselves
generally more positively.

00:03:16.880 --> 00:03:20.170
And we are more likely to help,
trust, and cooperate

00:03:20.170 --> 00:03:21.680
with members of our group.

00:03:21.680 --> 00:03:23.720
So this is Buffy.

00:03:23.720 --> 00:03:26.295
Show of hands, familiar with
"Buffy, the Vampire Slayer"?

00:03:26.295 --> 00:03:27.300
OK, great.

00:03:27.300 --> 00:03:29.480
So this is her.

00:03:29.480 --> 00:03:30.660
And the Scoobies.

00:03:30.660 --> 00:03:33.180
And eventually, it includes
vampires.

00:03:33.180 --> 00:03:35.660
So the "us" gets wider.

00:03:35.660 --> 00:03:38.300
And it's not simply vampires
versus humans.

00:03:38.300 --> 00:03:40.580
But it becomes a little
bit more complex.

00:03:40.580 --> 00:03:43.420
And the ingroup, everyone has
their own back story.

00:03:43.420 --> 00:03:45.280
It's interesting.

00:03:45.280 --> 00:03:49.080
That's another us,
DC superheroes.

00:03:49.080 --> 00:03:52.490
And so we are prone to divide
the world into "us" versus

00:03:52.490 --> 00:03:56.450
"them." And whenever we do, we
amplify the differences.

00:03:56.450 --> 00:03:58.650
Blue eyes versus brown eyes--

00:03:58.650 --> 00:04:00.510
I don't know how many--
elementary school, there was

00:04:00.510 --> 00:04:03.930
this program going
on for kids.

00:04:03.930 --> 00:04:06.230
Now being different can
refer to variety

00:04:06.230 --> 00:04:07.490
of different qualities.

00:04:07.490 --> 00:04:10.050
You can be physically different,
like Nightcrawler,

00:04:10.050 --> 00:04:15.270
who is blue and has a tail
and can teleport.

00:04:15.270 --> 00:04:18.769
This is a version of the Bat
Girl character, Barbara

00:04:18.769 --> 00:04:21.459
Gordon, where her back is
broken by the Joker.

00:04:21.459 --> 00:04:24.480
And so she's in a wheelchair.

00:04:24.480 --> 00:04:26.070
You can be psychologically
different.

00:04:26.070 --> 00:04:30.250
These are five different
psychological dimensions of

00:04:30.250 --> 00:04:31.390
personality.

00:04:31.390 --> 00:04:36.440
And so people fall on each
of the five lines.

00:04:36.440 --> 00:04:39.810
They'll have a point on which
they fall on those dimensions.

00:04:39.810 --> 00:04:44.790
And your profile will be unique
because, really, the

00:04:44.790 --> 00:04:46.770
points are infinite
on the continuum.

00:04:46.770 --> 00:04:49.040
And so you are different.

00:04:49.040 --> 00:04:51.480
People at the extremes
are quite different.

00:04:51.480 --> 00:04:53.960
But everyone is different,
psychologically,

00:04:53.960 --> 00:04:54.810
from someone else.

00:04:54.810 --> 00:04:56.410
You can be different by
virtue of having an

00:04:56.410 --> 00:04:58.770
unusual personal history.

00:04:58.770 --> 00:05:01.810
For instance, Bruce Wayne
witnessed his parents' death.

00:05:01.810 --> 00:05:04.370
Hopefully, that is unusual.

00:05:04.370 --> 00:05:05.990
But, unfortunately, he's
not the only one

00:05:05.990 --> 00:05:08.320
who's experienced that.

00:05:08.320 --> 00:05:10.490
So there are a lot of different
ways to be and feel

00:05:10.490 --> 00:05:12.960
different within a given
social context.

00:05:12.960 --> 00:05:13.930
And I'm going to come
back to the

00:05:13.930 --> 00:05:16.560
importance of social context.

00:05:16.560 --> 00:05:18.930
So this is normal curve,
the bell curve.

00:05:18.930 --> 00:05:21.300
People are undoubtedly
familiar with it.

00:05:21.300 --> 00:05:23.790
And we typically think of being
different as being in

00:05:23.790 --> 00:05:26.970
the yellow parts, or
maybe part of the

00:05:26.970 --> 00:05:29.150
reddish pink parts.

00:05:29.150 --> 00:05:33.770
And psychologically, depends on
what you're talking about,

00:05:33.770 --> 00:05:38.820
whether being different is
restricted to the tails.

00:05:38.820 --> 00:05:42.000
Basically because of the social
categorization "us"

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:45.070
versus "them" phenomenon,
whenever you're feeling

00:05:45.070 --> 00:05:47.590
different about something, it
puts you at risk to feel part

00:05:47.590 --> 00:05:50.990
of the outgroup when you're
out in the larger world.

00:05:50.990 --> 00:05:55.860
So you could be in the blue
normal curve, the biggest

00:05:55.860 --> 00:05:59.290
part, the most frequent part
of the bell curve.

00:05:59.290 --> 00:06:02.610
But if you're with people who
are in either of the yellow

00:06:02.610 --> 00:06:04.960
parts, you will feel different,
even though

00:06:04.960 --> 00:06:06.840
statistically you're not.

00:06:06.840 --> 00:06:08.810
But that won't matter.

00:06:08.810 --> 00:06:12.030
Your psychological experience of
being different is totally

00:06:12.030 --> 00:06:16.000
based on your social context.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:20.850
So if you were really smart, for
instance, and didn't have

00:06:20.850 --> 00:06:24.370
a magnet class or a magnet
school, and you were with

00:06:24.370 --> 00:06:27.670
other kids who weren't as
smart or gifted in a

00:06:27.670 --> 00:06:29.410
particular way, you would
feel different.

00:06:29.410 --> 00:06:32.050
But if you had gone to a magnet
school with other

00:06:32.050 --> 00:06:34.850
people like you, you wouldn't
feel different.

00:06:34.850 --> 00:06:36.330
Everybody with me on that?

00:06:36.330 --> 00:06:40.050
How many people here went to
some kind of special school,

00:06:40.050 --> 00:06:42.320
magnet school?

00:06:42.320 --> 00:06:44.530
Interesting.

00:06:44.530 --> 00:06:47.520
So this is the Thing from
the Fantastic Four.

00:06:47.520 --> 00:06:52.080
And he is walking through a
glass doorway, which breaks

00:06:52.080 --> 00:06:53.370
because he's too big for it.

00:06:53.370 --> 00:06:56.070
And he says, "Why must they
build doorways so narrow?"

00:06:56.070 --> 00:06:59.950
And the point here is simply
that, again, when he's out in

00:06:59.950 --> 00:07:02.880
the social world of everybody
else, all the people in the

00:07:02.880 --> 00:07:06.960
blue part of the normal curve,
he feels really different,

00:07:06.960 --> 00:07:08.730
which isn't as noticeable
depending

00:07:08.730 --> 00:07:10.990
on his social context.

00:07:10.990 --> 00:07:14.460
So being different usually
means being part of an

00:07:14.460 --> 00:07:16.930
outgroup unless you're fortunate
to be in a place

00:07:16.930 --> 00:07:19.490
where there are lots of other
different people like you.

00:07:19.490 --> 00:07:21.520
So it's a little bit of a
problem to be different.

00:07:21.520 --> 00:07:23.340
And you may have experienced
this.

00:07:23.340 --> 00:07:26.430
There's this tension between
wanting to either be or appear

00:07:26.430 --> 00:07:29.940
normal, to fit in, to be like
everybody else in your social

00:07:29.940 --> 00:07:33.690
context, versus accepting
yourself as you are.

00:07:33.690 --> 00:07:36.070
Because if you want to be or
appear normal, there's a part

00:07:36.070 --> 00:07:38.250
where you don't like yourself,
which is an

00:07:38.250 --> 00:07:41.450
uncomfortable way to be.

