And in contrast to when the
Thing is out in public

00:11:48.890 --> 00:11:53.400
breaking glass doorways, when
he's with other people who are

00:11:53.400 --> 00:11:56.940
sort of like him in that they
got morphed, he can be really

00:11:56.940 --> 00:12:02.230
comfortable and be himself
and feel proud and good.

00:12:02.230 --> 00:12:05.610
"X-Men First Class," when they
find each other, again, it's

00:12:05.610 --> 00:12:11.230
about finding your people,
if you will.

00:12:11.230 --> 00:12:14.020
Whoops--and that was "The
Incredibles" when they

00:12:14.020 --> 00:12:18.380
acknowledge their differences
and don their tights.

00:12:18.380 --> 00:12:21.670
So how can you make being
different work for you?

00:12:21.670 --> 00:12:25.730
So superheroes teach us to
recognize and acknowledge the

00:12:25.730 --> 00:12:26.700
ways that we're different.

00:12:26.700 --> 00:12:27.060
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:12:27.060 --> 00:12:29.390
-But Dad always said our powers
were nothing to be

00:12:29.390 --> 00:12:29.960
ashamed of.

00:12:29.960 --> 00:12:31.290
Our powers made us special.

00:12:31.290 --> 00:12:32.780
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:12:32.780 --> 00:12:34.890
ROBIN ROSENBERG: Thank
you, Dash.

00:12:34.890 --> 00:12:39.970
So with recognition, when you
acknowledge and recognize,

00:12:39.970 --> 00:12:41.920
comes exploration.

00:12:41.920 --> 00:12:43.880
Again, these three little
steps are what

00:12:43.880 --> 00:12:45.310
superheroes teach us.

00:12:45.310 --> 00:12:48.450
When you realize you're
different, you want to know,

00:12:48.450 --> 00:12:49.610
so what does that mean?

00:12:49.610 --> 00:12:51.300
What are the parameters
about being different?

00:12:51.300 --> 00:12:53.560
How different am I?

00:12:53.560 --> 00:12:58.060
So, from the TV show "Heroes,"
this young woman realizes this

00:12:58.060 --> 00:12:59.450
she's never been sick.

00:12:59.450 --> 00:13:01.580
If she hurts herself, she
gets better right away.

00:13:01.580 --> 00:13:05.260
So in exploring, she puts her
hand down the garbage disposal

00:13:05.260 --> 00:13:07.260
and turns it on.

00:13:07.260 --> 00:13:08.920
It heals right away.

00:13:08.920 --> 00:13:10.170
It was a little cool CGI.

00:13:10.170 --> 00:13:12.600
But exploration is
really important.

00:13:12.600 --> 00:13:18.350
This is a schematic of
Spiderman's spider-injecting,

00:13:18.350 --> 00:13:22.150
spider-webbing stuff.

00:13:22.150 --> 00:13:23.650
It's a little creepy,
the idea that it

00:13:23.650 --> 00:13:26.530
comes out of his wrist.

00:13:26.530 --> 00:13:29.240
But it was a schematic so he
could understand and explore.

00:13:29.240 --> 00:13:30.780
What are the limits of this?

00:13:30.780 --> 00:13:31.920
What are the parameters?

00:13:31.920 --> 00:13:35.420
And in the film, he tries to see
how much he can get away

00:13:35.420 --> 00:13:38.070
with without going on empty.

00:13:38.070 --> 00:13:39.730
And this is what happens
when you don't explore.

00:13:39.730 --> 00:13:41.880
This is not a DC Comic.

00:13:41.880 --> 00:13:44.440
It says, "Superboy politely
apologizes for ripping some

00:13:44.440 --> 00:13:47.250
dude's arm off." And he says,
"Aw man, I'm sorry.

00:13:47.250 --> 00:13:51.020
That's totally my bad." Because
he didn't know the

00:13:51.020 --> 00:13:52.660
limits of his strength.

00:13:52.660 --> 00:13:55.530
This is a version in which he
did not explore the parameters

00:13:55.530 --> 00:13:58.440
of his ability to
be different.

00:13:58.440 --> 00:14:00.990
Also, there's control.

00:14:00.990 --> 00:14:05.400
So one of the things that Luke
Skywalker does is learn to

00:14:05.400 --> 00:14:08.970
control the ways that
he's different.

00:14:08.970 --> 00:14:11.440
Buffy learns to control.

00:14:11.440 --> 00:14:12.880
She has some super strength.

00:14:12.880 --> 00:14:15.430
She learns to control that.

00:14:15.430 --> 00:14:18.650
The other thing that happens
when you're different and you

00:14:18.650 --> 00:14:22.770
acknowledge that is you
hopefully will decide to what

00:14:22.770 --> 00:14:26.950
purpose should that
different-ness be put.

00:14:26.950 --> 00:14:29.910
Superman, Clark Kent, struggles
with the gifts that

00:14:29.910 --> 00:14:32.950
he's been given and how
should he use them.

00:14:32.950 --> 00:14:37.790
NPR a while back had a
little radio poll.

00:14:37.790 --> 00:14:40.040
If you could have a superpower,
what would it be?

00:14:40.040 --> 00:14:43.060
And people would say, oh, X-ray
vision so I could see in

00:14:43.060 --> 00:14:45.180
the girls' locker room,
or invisibility

00:14:45.180 --> 00:14:46.420
and I'd rob a bank.

00:14:46.420 --> 00:14:49.150
And I think at some point,
it gets kind of boring.

00:14:49.150 --> 00:14:51.610
You know, how many girls' locker
rooms you want to look

00:14:51.610 --> 00:14:54.300
in before you decide,
OK, now what?

00:14:54.300 --> 00:14:56.410
And that's--

00:14:56.410 --> 00:15:00.660
I mean, unless you're
a really early

00:15:00.660 --> 00:15:03.670
pubescent teenager or something.

00:15:03.670 --> 00:15:07.300
So purpose becomes
really important.

00:15:07.300 --> 00:15:09.760
All the superheroes have this.

00:15:09.760 --> 00:15:11.610
They have an ability.

00:15:11.610 --> 00:15:13.060
How do they want to use it?

00:15:13.060 --> 00:15:15.270
That's Hermione Granger,
who's definitely a

00:15:15.270 --> 00:15:17.420
superhero in my book.

00:15:17.420 --> 00:15:20.160
Tony Stark, Iron Man.

00:15:20.160 --> 00:15:23.280
So the other thing superheroes
teach us is to band together

00:15:23.280 --> 00:15:24.990
with like-minded folks.

00:15:24.990 --> 00:15:30.260
So these are the X-Men,
Fantastic Four, DC

00:15:30.260 --> 00:15:31.030
superheroes.

00:15:31.030 --> 00:15:33.510
So this is Comic-Con,
banding together

00:15:33.510 --> 00:15:36.260
with like-minded folks.

00:15:36.260 --> 00:15:38.080
I don't know what these people
are, but they're clearly

00:15:38.080 --> 00:15:41.710
banding together and they're
like-minded.

00:15:41.710 --> 00:15:43.400
Banding together with
like-minded folks--

00:15:43.400 --> 00:15:44.850
I mean, people are amazing.

00:15:44.850 --> 00:15:47.770
There's so many different ways
we can be different.

00:15:47.770 --> 00:15:49.340
Banding together with
like-minded folks.

00:15:49.340 --> 00:15:51.590
Sometimes you are
the only one.

00:15:51.590 --> 00:15:53.630
There is no one else like you.

00:15:53.630 --> 00:15:57.890
And so in the middle, this is
Clark Kent from "Smallville."

00:15:57.890 --> 00:15:59.880
And until his cousin appears,
there is no

00:15:59.880 --> 00:16:02.110
other alien from Krypton.

00:16:02.110 --> 00:16:05.440
So the best you can do is band
together with people who

00:16:05.440 --> 00:16:08.650
accept the ways that you're
different and support you.

00:16:08.650 --> 00:16:11.870
And those are his friends who
know that he's super.

00:16:11.870 --> 00:16:13.900
This is Hell Boy
and Abe Sapien.

00:16:13.900 --> 00:16:16.530
They are the only
ones on Earth.

00:16:16.530 --> 00:16:19.940
But they band together with
people who support them.

00:16:19.940 --> 00:16:22.600
So lesson one, acknowledge
the ways in

00:16:22.600 --> 00:16:23.790
which you're different.

00:16:23.790 --> 00:16:25.750
Until you claim it is a part
of yourself, you'll be

00:16:25.750 --> 00:16:27.040
fighting against it.

00:16:27.040 --> 00:16:29.485
Explore the boundaries of
your different-ness.

00:16:29.485 --> 00:16:32.090
Learn to control it.

00:16:32.090 --> 00:16:34.120
Think about how you
want to use it.

00:16:34.120 --> 00:16:36.620
And then band together with
like-minded folks.

00:16:36.620 --> 00:16:40.010
OK, so each of us is different
from everyone else.

00:16:40.010 --> 00:16:41.910
But we're similar in
that we're all

00:16:41.910 --> 00:16:43.660
different from each other.

00:16:43.660 --> 00:16:44.540
That's the take-home message.

00:16:44.540 --> 00:16:45.250
All right.

00:16:45.250 --> 00:16:47.250
Adversity can be overcome.

00:16:47.250 --> 00:16:51.420
Show of hands, how many people
here have experience--

00:16:51.420 --> 00:16:54.100
I'm not going to ask any more
details than this--

00:16:54.100 --> 00:16:56.530
experienced a traumatic stress
or significant adversity?

00:16:59.370 --> 00:17:02.610
How many people have not?

00:17:02.610 --> 00:17:03.760
You are really lucky.

00:17:03.760 --> 00:17:05.099
And I hope that that lasts.

00:17:05.099 --> 00:17:07.700
Most people will in their
lifetimes experience

00:17:07.700 --> 00:17:10.430
significant adversity.

00:17:10.430 --> 00:17:13.400
And a fun fact to
know and tell--

00:17:13.400 --> 00:17:15.270
well, actually, first let me ask
you this other question.

00:17:15.270 --> 00:17:20.470
So based on what you know of
the world, if someone has a

00:17:20.470 --> 00:17:23.880
traumatic event, do you think
the likelihood is greater than

00:17:23.880 --> 00:17:25.250
50% that they'll develop

00:17:25.250 --> 00:17:26.920
post-traumatic stress disorder?

00:17:26.920 --> 00:17:29.490
So if you agree that at least
50% of the people who

00:17:29.490 --> 00:17:33.700
experience the trauma will get
PTSD, raise your hand.

00:17:33.700 --> 00:17:34.950
Wow.

00:17:37.120 --> 00:17:39.310
As a psychologist, I was in this
group until I read the

00:17:39.310 --> 00:17:43.790
statistic that only 20% of
people who experience a trauma

00:17:43.790 --> 00:17:46.670
go on to develop PTSD, which is
not what's portrayed in the

00:17:46.670 --> 00:17:49.660
films and movies and books.

00:17:49.660 --> 00:17:51.820
And so I just thought that
was really interesting.

00:17:51.820 --> 00:17:54.620
And we know a lot at now about
what makes people more

00:17:54.620 --> 00:17:55.920
vulnerable to developing it.

00:17:55.920 --> 00:17:58.280
But I'm not talking
about PTSD today.

00:17:58.280 --> 00:18:00.030
It's a little interesting
fact.

00:18:00.030 --> 00:18:03.635
I want to talk about the 80% of
people, and the people who

00:18:03.635 --> 00:18:06.520
have PTSD who moved
past it, which is

00:18:06.520 --> 00:18:08.940
adversity can be overcome.

00:18:08.940 --> 00:18:10.300
Many superheroes have

00:18:10.300 --> 00:18:12.720
experienced significant adversity.

00:18:12.720 --> 00:18:18.080
Just to name a few, we've got
Peter Parker, who initiated a

00:18:18.080 --> 00:18:21.410
series of events that led to
the murder of his beloved

00:18:21.410 --> 00:18:23.650
uncle and guardian Ben.

00:18:23.650 --> 00:18:24.490
Prof.

00:18:24.490 --> 00:18:28.050
Charles Xavier is a telepath and
was through the Holocaust

00:18:28.050 --> 00:18:31.690
and experienced many peoples'
deaths in his mind.

00:18:31.690 --> 00:18:32.940
Jean Grey is similar.

00:18:32.940 --> 00:18:35.890
As a kid, she's a telepath and
experienced the death of her

00:18:35.890 --> 00:18:39.500
friend in a car crash, depending
on which version.

00:18:39.500 --> 00:18:42.040
Anakin Skywalker, where
do we start?

00:18:42.040 --> 00:18:46.463
But he witnessed the torture and
then death of his mother,

00:18:46.463 --> 00:18:49.860
then turned to the dark side.

00:18:49.860 --> 00:18:53.070
Many of us, as I said, have
experienced some kind of

00:18:53.070 --> 00:18:56.570
traumatic stressor or
significant adversity.

00:18:56.570 --> 00:18:57.350
How are we doing on time?

00:18:57.350 --> 00:18:58.930
OK.

00:18:58.930 --> 00:19:05.480
I'm going to skip over the
specific kind of stressors and

00:19:05.480 --> 00:19:08.940
adversity that people can have
because we know them.

00:19:08.940 --> 00:19:12.140
But if we look at our
superheroes, what type did

00:19:12.140 --> 00:19:13.280
they experience?

00:19:13.280 --> 00:19:15.980
So this is Bruce Wayne
and witnessed the

00:19:15.980 --> 00:19:17.070
murder of his parents.

00:19:17.070 --> 00:19:18.900
And his own life
was in danger.

00:19:18.900 --> 00:19:23.330
And then I'm going to show you
Tony stark from "Iron Man 1."

00:19:23.330 --> 00:19:25.330
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:19:32.830 --> 00:19:34.160
ROBIN ROSENBERG: And for those
of you in the know, in the

00:19:34.160 --> 00:19:37.550
film, in contrast to the comics,
this was intended.

00:19:37.550 --> 00:19:41.720
He was the target versus him
being an accidental target in

00:19:41.720 --> 00:19:44.615
the comic, which actually makes
the story, I think, I

00:19:44.615 --> 00:19:46.000
think a bit richer.

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:48.930
Intended personal violence is
the one that tends to leave

00:19:48.930 --> 00:19:50.040
the biggest wake.

00:19:50.040 --> 00:19:54.390
So if you were assaulted versus
in a natural disaster,

00:19:54.390 --> 00:19:59.990
you're more likely to have a
bigger psychological effect.

00:19:59.990 --> 00:20:03.700
People cope with adversity and
trauma by making meaning of

00:20:03.700 --> 00:20:05.790
their events and aftermath.

00:20:05.790 --> 00:20:08.450
And they understand it in a
larger framework about the

00:20:08.450 --> 00:20:09.790
meaning of life.

00:20:09.790 --> 00:20:13.770
So for most of us, before
adversity hits, we have a set

00:20:13.770 --> 00:20:15.610
of global beliefs.

00:20:15.610 --> 00:20:20.170
They include a belief in a just
world, which is that you

00:20:20.170 --> 00:20:22.265
deserve what you get and you
get what you deserve.

00:20:22.265 --> 00:20:24.970
It's a little circular,
a little childish, but

00:20:24.970 --> 00:20:28.530
nonetheless, that we're
human, that it's

00:20:28.530 --> 00:20:30.010
possible to trust others--

00:20:30.010 --> 00:20:31.900
not all others, but
there are some

00:20:31.900 --> 00:20:33.730
trustworthy people out there--

00:20:33.730 --> 00:20:37.820
and that it's possible to be
effective in the world.

00:20:37.820 --> 00:20:41.190
These beliefs drive
our global goals.

00:20:41.190 --> 00:20:44.540
Whatever we're striving toward,
we're striving because

00:20:44.540 --> 00:20:47.720
we believe that if we work hard,
we'll have an effect.

00:20:47.720 --> 00:20:50.100
That if we work at a
relationship, you know

00:20:50.100 --> 00:20:51.740
inherently the person
will be trustworthy.

00:20:51.740 --> 00:20:55.530
We should try to find friends
and an intimate partner.

00:20:55.530 --> 00:21:00.380
And that if we do good, we
should get good-- a belief in

00:21:00.380 --> 00:21:02.180
a just world.

00:21:02.180 --> 00:21:06.050
And then the beliefs and the
goals give us a sense that

00:21:06.050 --> 00:21:07.170
life has purpose.

00:21:07.170 --> 00:21:08.180
We're moving forward.

00:21:08.180 --> 00:21:10.660
We have meaning.

00:21:10.660 --> 00:21:12.550
Unfortunately, when you
experience significant

00:21:12.550 --> 00:21:16.720
adversity or trauma, you say,
why did this happen?

00:21:16.720 --> 00:21:19.890
Or if a loved one experienced
it, why did it happen to them?

00:21:19.890 --> 00:21:22.640
Because it really challenges
a belief in a just world.

00:21:22.640 --> 00:21:25.510
If I'm a basically good person
and something bad happens to

00:21:25.510 --> 00:21:27.710
me, does it mean
I deserved it?

00:21:27.710 --> 00:21:30.420
Because I get what I deserve
and I deserve what I get.

00:21:30.420 --> 00:21:34.770
So it challenges the beliefs.

00:21:34.770 --> 00:21:37.730
Oh, whoops, wrong button.

00:21:37.730 --> 00:21:41.580
So, again, it challenges
belief in a just world.

00:21:41.580 --> 00:21:45.200
If the trauma or adversity
involved another person who

00:21:45.200 --> 00:21:48.470
was untrustworthy that we
trusted, it calls into

00:21:48.470 --> 00:21:51.200
question our ability to evaluate
people and decide who

00:21:51.200 --> 00:21:52.470
is trustworthy and who isn't.

00:21:52.470 --> 00:21:54.770
And that's pretty scary.

00:21:54.770 --> 00:21:58.330
And if we weren't able to
protect ourselves or the other

00:21:58.330 --> 00:22:01.100
person that we care about, then
how can we be effective

00:22:01.100 --> 00:22:02.220
in the world?

00:22:02.220 --> 00:22:04.260
Because that's really the most
important thing is to really

00:22:04.260 --> 00:22:06.720
protect yourself or
other people.

00:22:06.720 --> 00:22:10.090
And these are pretty grim
existential questions that

00:22:10.090 --> 00:22:14.140
people ask themselves after
adversity or a trauma.

00:22:14.140 --> 00:22:17.460
So you question your global
beliefs which causes you to

00:22:17.460 --> 00:22:18.410
question your goals.

00:22:18.410 --> 00:22:20.400
Because why am I working
so hard if I

00:22:20.400 --> 00:22:21.580
don't get what I deserve?

00:22:21.580 --> 00:22:24.450
If I can't be effective,
what's the point?

00:22:24.450 --> 00:22:29.840
And, in fact, life can feel
meaningless and purposeless.

00:22:29.840 --> 00:22:30.930
There's a natural process.

00:22:30.930 --> 00:22:32.210
People work through this.

00:22:32.210 --> 00:22:35.200
Human beings are absolutely
amazing.

00:22:35.200 --> 00:22:37.600
And part of how we work through
it and the process of

00:22:37.600 --> 00:22:39.620
working through it is to develop
a fuller understanding

00:22:39.620 --> 00:22:43.380
of why the negative events
happened, thinking through the

00:22:43.380 --> 00:22:46.360
implications, which may be
changing the idea that you

00:22:46.360 --> 00:22:47.660
don't get what you deserve--

00:22:47.660 --> 00:22:49.720
you know, life isn't fair--

00:22:49.720 --> 00:22:53.710
discovering possible silver
linings; recognizing that

00:22:53.710 --> 00:22:57.800
other people are often worse
off, and putting the events in

00:22:57.800 --> 00:23:00.150
a broader context.

00:23:00.150 --> 00:23:04.490
So with resolution, people get
a heightened sense of self

00:23:04.490 --> 00:23:06.470
where they're aware of
their vulnerability.

00:23:06.470 --> 00:23:08.200
They appreciate life more.

00:23:08.200 --> 00:23:11.860
And Nietzsche was right, a sense
of being stronger for

00:23:11.860 --> 00:23:15.300
having survived.

00:23:15.300 --> 00:23:19.380
They have an increased
connection to other people.

00:23:19.380 --> 00:23:22.010
They're more expressive
emotionally, more disclosing

00:23:22.010 --> 00:23:25.360
about what happened to them,
and, in general, an increased

00:23:25.360 --> 00:23:27.130
empathy for others.

00:23:27.130 --> 00:23:29.210
And they have an altered
philosophy of life.

00:23:29.210 --> 00:23:34.270
And this is, I think, where
superheroes model for us.

00:23:34.270 --> 00:23:35.630
They're more spiritual.

00:23:35.630 --> 00:23:36.940
They live life more fully.

00:23:36.940 --> 00:23:38.726
But they're also social
activists.

00:23:41.490 --> 00:23:43.520
So I'm going to go through
the story of Batman.

00:23:43.520 --> 00:23:45.800
Does anyone here not know
Batman's origin story?

00:23:49.110 --> 00:23:50.390
Great.

00:23:50.390 --> 00:23:53.610
Really quick, bottom panel's
his parents get killed.

00:23:53.610 --> 00:23:55.750
This is the original 1939
comic, by the way.

00:23:55.750 --> 00:23:57.530
It was his back story
developed in the

00:23:57.530 --> 00:24:00.080
sixth Batman comic.

00:24:00.080 --> 00:24:03.170
Bruce Wayne is incredibly
precocious in so many ways.

00:24:03.170 --> 00:24:06.920
And so the important panel is
the last one, which is "Days

00:24:06.920 --> 00:24:10.970
later, a curious and strange
scene takes place." For most

00:24:10.970 --> 00:24:12.190
people, this is not days.

00:24:12.190 --> 00:24:14.020
This may not even be
weeks or months.

00:24:14.020 --> 00:24:16.840
But because he's Bruce Wayne,
it happens in days.

00:24:16.840 --> 00:24:19.340
"And I swear by the spirit of
my parents to avenge their

00:24:19.340 --> 00:24:22.190
deaths by spending the rest
of my life warring on all

