00:35:59.260 --> 00:36:01.804
OK, why?

00:36:01.804 --> 00:36:03.160
AUDIENCE: The hair.

00:36:03.160 --> 00:36:04.430
ROBIN ROSENBERG: The hair?

00:36:04.430 --> 00:36:07.020
No, it's the Superman
little twisty thing.

00:36:07.020 --> 00:36:07.610
No, that's true.

00:36:07.610 --> 00:36:07.890
AUDIENCE: Square--

00:36:07.890 --> 00:36:08.306
ROBIN ROSENBERG: What?

00:36:08.306 --> 00:36:09.140
AUDIENCE: Square jaw.

00:36:09.140 --> 00:36:10.240
ROBIN ROSENBERG: Square
jaw, yep.

00:36:10.240 --> 00:36:10.580
OK.

00:36:10.580 --> 00:36:12.490
Cleft chin, right?

00:36:12.490 --> 00:36:13.390
Any other thoughts?

00:36:13.390 --> 00:36:14.080
AUDIENCE: Smiling.

00:36:14.080 --> 00:36:15.880
ROBIN ROSENBERG: Smiling, OK.

00:36:15.880 --> 00:36:16.740
AUDIENCE: Nice cape.

00:36:16.740 --> 00:36:19.232
ROBIN ROSENBERG:
Nice cape, OK.

00:36:19.232 --> 00:36:20.570
AUDIENCE: Common pose, too.

00:36:20.570 --> 00:36:22.020
ROBIN ROSENBERG: Common
pose, OK.

00:36:22.020 --> 00:36:26.230
So all of this happened
instantly, before I even asked

00:36:26.230 --> 00:36:27.270
you a question about it.

00:36:27.270 --> 00:36:30.330
Once you saw it, you made all
of these assumptions.

00:36:30.330 --> 00:36:34.380
So you looked at the cleft chin,
and you inferred other

00:36:34.380 --> 00:36:35.800
qualities about it.

00:36:35.800 --> 00:36:38.360
So in real life, we have
examples of this

00:36:38.360 --> 00:36:39.490
in our daily life.

00:36:39.490 --> 00:36:42.310
These are well-founded,
well-researched things.

00:36:42.310 --> 00:36:45.860
So we think that good-looking
people are kinder,

00:36:45.860 --> 00:36:50.470
which is not true.

00:36:50.470 --> 00:36:53.730
I mean, a given person may or
may not be, but in general,

00:36:53.730 --> 00:36:55.830
good looking people
aren't kinder.

00:36:55.830 --> 00:36:57.450
And that we think
well-groomed job

00:36:57.450 --> 00:36:58.700
applicants are more competent.

00:37:03.340 --> 00:37:06.610
But, again, we are making all
these assumptions because it

00:37:06.610 --> 00:37:10.000
helps us get by with less
cognitive effort.

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:13.140
OK, so there's a flip side of
this called the Devil Effect

00:37:13.140 --> 00:37:14.820
or the Horn Effect.

00:37:14.820 --> 00:37:18.020
And if someone has undesirable
attributes, then we infer that

00:37:18.020 --> 00:37:21.250
the person has additional
related negative attributes.

00:37:21.250 --> 00:37:23.142
So hero or villain?

00:37:23.142 --> 00:37:24.440
AUDIENCE: Villain.

00:37:24.440 --> 00:37:24.930
ROBIN ROSENBERG: Villain.

00:37:24.930 --> 00:37:26.296
Why?

00:37:26.296 --> 00:37:28.250
AUDIENCE: Dark colors.

00:37:28.250 --> 00:37:28.710
ROBIN ROSENBERG: Say?

00:37:28.710 --> 00:37:29.860
AUDIENCE: Dark colors.

00:37:29.860 --> 00:37:30.740
ROBIN ROSENBERG: Dark colors.

00:37:30.740 --> 00:37:32.731
OK.

00:37:32.731 --> 00:37:33.570
AUDIENCE: Scowling.

00:37:33.570 --> 00:37:35.610
ROBIN ROSENBERG: Scowling,
frown, yep.

00:37:35.610 --> 00:37:38.180
AUDIENCE: Small head compared
to the body.

00:37:38.180 --> 00:37:40.772
ROBIN ROSENBERG: Small
head, right.

00:37:40.772 --> 00:37:42.680
AUDIENCE: He's looking
down at us.

00:37:42.680 --> 00:37:44.170
ROBIN ROSENBERG: He's
looking down at us.

00:37:44.170 --> 00:37:45.070
Cool, OK.

00:37:45.070 --> 00:37:46.450
AUDIENCE: His arms
are crossed.

00:37:46.450 --> 00:37:47.460
ROBIN ROSENBERG: His
arms are crossed.

00:37:47.460 --> 00:37:48.060
OK.

00:37:48.060 --> 00:37:48.600
Cool.

00:37:48.600 --> 00:37:53.470
Now, ironically, this stance is
very close to the Superman

00:37:53.470 --> 00:37:56.190
stance, which is legs spread.

00:37:56.190 --> 00:37:58.680
Its hands on hips.

00:37:58.680 --> 00:38:01.710
We have seen Superman
in this pose.

00:38:01.710 --> 00:38:03.320
So it's not simply the pose.

00:38:03.320 --> 00:38:05.470
But you see how all of a sudden,
you saw this and you

00:38:05.470 --> 00:38:08.350
instantly made a decision,
villain.

00:38:08.350 --> 00:38:10.850
The metallic part
probably helped.

00:38:10.850 --> 00:38:11.840
I assume it's metallic.

00:38:11.840 --> 00:38:15.250
I'm not sure, but it's
shiny like metal.

00:38:15.250 --> 00:38:19.540
And so we made all of
these attributes.

00:38:19.540 --> 00:38:20.790
So I'm going to tell
you about a study--

00:38:23.160 --> 00:38:24.530
people are already laughing.

00:38:24.530 --> 00:38:27.210
So there was a study
that was done.

00:38:27.210 --> 00:38:30.230
And you, as a participant, were
brought into the lab.

00:38:30.230 --> 00:38:32.530
And you were shown photographs
of people.

00:38:32.530 --> 00:38:34.850
Some of them were wearing
a plain T-shirt.

00:38:34.850 --> 00:38:36.370
And some of them were
wearing what I'd

00:38:36.370 --> 00:38:37.325
call an alcohol T-shirt.

00:38:37.325 --> 00:38:40.400
It had Jack Daniels or
something on it.

00:38:43.600 --> 00:38:47.220
In the photograph in the lab,
I had the same person.

00:38:47.220 --> 00:38:48.770
Sometimes it was plain.

00:38:48.770 --> 00:38:50.410
And I had photographs
of it being plain.

00:38:50.410 --> 00:38:52.270
And I had photographs
of it being alcohol.

00:38:52.270 --> 00:38:55.970
So the people are the same.

00:38:55.970 --> 00:39:00.050
It's just we both conditions,
if you will.

00:39:00.050 --> 00:39:03.130
You were asked to rate people,
just like tell us what you

00:39:03.130 --> 00:39:04.220
think about this person.

00:39:04.220 --> 00:39:06.520
And some of those people wearing
a plain T-shirt and

00:39:06.520 --> 00:39:09.690
some of them were wearing
an alcohol T-shirt.

00:39:09.690 --> 00:39:14.010
Nothing else was different
except the alcohol words.

00:39:14.010 --> 00:39:18.180
So what the participants said
is that the people in the

00:39:18.180 --> 00:39:19.770
photographs who were
wearing an alcohol

00:39:19.770 --> 00:39:21.470
T-shirt were rated as--

00:39:21.470 --> 00:39:22.920
long list--

00:39:22.920 --> 00:39:26.050
less honest, less independent,
less responsible, less

00:39:26.050 --> 00:39:28.820
reliable, less religious, less
likely to be on time, less

00:39:28.820 --> 00:39:31.050
likely to do well in school.

00:39:31.050 --> 00:39:33.940
They were more likely to smoke,
to be a party animal,

00:39:33.940 --> 00:39:35.990
drink or swear, and
be risk-taker.

00:39:35.990 --> 00:39:43.500
All of this inferred
from alcohol words.

00:39:43.500 --> 00:39:45.520
I think it's probably true.

00:39:45.520 --> 00:39:48.450
I mean, I know I should know
better, but I would make the

00:39:48.450 --> 00:39:49.350
same assumptions.

00:39:49.350 --> 00:39:51.990
But we don't know where the
person got the T-shirt.

00:39:51.990 --> 00:39:52.950
It was a gift, it was--

00:39:52.950 --> 00:39:56.080
I mean, It's just interesting
how all of this

00:39:56.080 --> 00:39:59.530
negative stuff came out.

00:39:59.530 --> 00:40:01.700
So social categorization
reduces the

00:40:01.700 --> 00:40:03.840
effort we have to expend.

00:40:03.840 --> 00:40:06.900
We don't have to think if the
guy in the cape was a bad guy.

00:40:06.900 --> 00:40:08.940
We just immediately make
these assumptions.

00:40:08.940 --> 00:40:13.360
But it makes us more likely
to make biased judgments.

00:40:13.360 --> 00:40:17.280
So people categorize us
based on how we dress.

00:40:17.280 --> 00:40:19.680
And then they treat
us accordingly.

00:40:19.680 --> 00:40:21.920
My mother was right.

00:40:21.920 --> 00:40:25.080
Now the interesting thing is
that the way they treat us can

00:40:25.080 --> 00:40:27.550
elicit certain behaviors
from us.

00:40:27.550 --> 00:40:30.870
And my mother didn't quite
tell me this part.

00:40:30.870 --> 00:40:33.000
Although I think she have
intuited because she's a good

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:33.950
lay psychologist.

00:40:33.950 --> 00:40:35.150
There was a study done.

00:40:35.150 --> 00:40:37.490
There was another study.

00:40:37.490 --> 00:40:39.110
You're brought into the lab.

00:40:39.110 --> 00:40:42.180
You are a woman.

00:40:42.180 --> 00:40:44.520
And you're told you're going
to have a telephone

00:40:44.520 --> 00:40:48.690
conversation with another
participant in the study.

00:40:48.690 --> 00:40:50.940
And so you go into this
cubicle, and you'll

00:40:50.940 --> 00:40:52.360
speak to him there.

00:40:52.360 --> 00:40:55.250
And whatever they told me,
to talk about whatever.

00:40:55.250 --> 00:40:58.960
If you are a guy and you came
into the lab, you were shown a

00:40:58.960 --> 00:40:59.770
photograph.

00:40:59.770 --> 00:41:03.750
And you were told this is the
woman you're going to talk to.

00:41:03.750 --> 00:41:05.210
Come into this cubicle.

00:41:05.210 --> 00:41:08.080
Now it turns out, half the guys
were shown a photograph

00:41:08.080 --> 00:41:09.840
of an attractive woman.

00:41:09.840 --> 00:41:11.870
And half the guys were shown
a photograph of an

00:41:11.870 --> 00:41:12.800
unattractive woman.

00:41:12.800 --> 00:41:15.530
And these were objectively
rated beforehand.

00:41:15.530 --> 00:41:17.000
People rated the photographs
of who is

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:18.750
attractive and who wasn't.

00:41:18.750 --> 00:41:21.300
These photographs had nothing to
do with the actual woman in

00:41:21.300 --> 00:41:23.980
the cubicle waiting to
talk to the guy.

00:41:23.980 --> 00:41:28.240
So just again to reiterate the
set-up, they're told they're

00:41:28.240 --> 00:41:30.260
going to talk to a woman who's
either attractive or

00:41:30.260 --> 00:41:31.650
unattractive.

00:41:31.650 --> 00:41:33.930
So that's the panel
on the left.

00:41:33.930 --> 00:41:36.850
In the middle panel, they
have their conversation.

00:41:36.850 --> 00:41:39.430
They're separately
tape-recorded.

00:41:39.430 --> 00:41:40.450
They leave the lab.

00:41:40.450 --> 00:41:42.160
They're done.

00:41:42.160 --> 00:41:46.800
In the lab, a rater who works
for the professor is listening

00:41:46.800 --> 00:41:50.050
to the women's part of the
conversation only.

00:41:50.050 --> 00:41:53.500
And they are rating her tone
of voice for warmth and

00:41:53.500 --> 00:41:54.420
friendliness.

00:41:54.420 --> 00:41:57.440
That's their job.

00:41:57.440 --> 00:41:58.520
And then they rate them.

00:41:58.520 --> 00:42:02.490
And then they look back and see
did the guys think that

00:42:02.490 --> 00:42:05.240
these were attractive women
or unattractive women.

00:42:05.240 --> 00:42:09.740
And it turns out that the women
who were rated as warm

00:42:09.740 --> 00:42:14.130
and friendly were the women
where the guy thought that she

00:42:14.130 --> 00:42:15.830
was going to be attractive.

00:42:15.830 --> 00:42:19.510
So what happened is the guy
thinks, I'm going to talk to

00:42:19.510 --> 00:42:21.990
someone who's attractive.

00:42:21.990 --> 00:42:27.360
And he somehow interacts with
her in a way that elicits this

00:42:27.360 --> 00:42:29.700
warmth and friendliness
from her.

00:42:29.700 --> 00:42:31.240
And he didn't even see her.

00:42:31.240 --> 00:42:33.140
It was just on the
phone, something

00:42:33.140 --> 00:42:35.000
in his tone of voice--

00:42:35.000 --> 00:42:37.600
they, it was a lot of guys,
it wasn't just one guy.

00:42:37.600 --> 00:42:43.080
Something elicited from her
behavior that made her conform

00:42:43.080 --> 00:42:45.110
to how he assumed she was.

00:42:48.660 --> 00:42:53.070
It becomes a self-fulfilling
prophecy where the way you

00:42:53.070 --> 00:42:55.930
dress causes people to treat
you accordingly.

00:42:55.930 --> 00:42:59.990
And how they treat you, then,
elicits that behavior from

00:42:59.990 --> 00:43:01.090
you, whether you
want to or not.

00:43:01.090 --> 00:43:02.130
It's all unconscious.

00:43:02.130 --> 00:43:06.410
This happens like in the
ether between people.

00:43:06.410 --> 00:43:07.610
It elicits the behavior.

00:43:07.610 --> 00:43:09.480
And it becomes a self-fulfilling
prophecy.

00:43:09.480 --> 00:43:12.760
So people will make inferences
about you based on your

00:43:12.760 --> 00:43:13.800
appearance.

00:43:13.800 --> 00:43:16.300
And most of the time, they
will not be Will Smith.

00:43:16.300 --> 00:43:18.340
They will not make that
extra effort and go

00:43:18.340 --> 00:43:20.480
beyond a snap judgment.

00:43:20.480 --> 00:43:24.020
So their judgments affect their
behavior, which affects

00:43:24.020 --> 00:43:26.420
your behavior and thoughts
and feelings without your

00:43:26.420 --> 00:43:28.050
knowing about it.

00:43:28.050 --> 00:43:30.080
And it becomes a self-fulfilling
prophecy.

00:43:30.080 --> 00:43:32.980
So what costume do
you want to wear?

00:43:32.980 --> 00:43:35.550
You should ask yourself what
part of yourself do you want

00:43:35.550 --> 00:43:37.160
to hide or express?

00:43:37.160 --> 00:43:39.100
What role do you want to play?

00:43:39.100 --> 00:43:41.730
What snap judgments do you want
other people to make of

00:43:41.730 --> 00:43:43.360
you because they will?

00:43:43.360 --> 00:43:44.830
Are you willing to have
these become a

00:43:44.830 --> 00:43:48.030
self-fulfilling prophecy?

00:43:48.030 --> 00:43:49.500
And I think we don't--

00:43:49.500 --> 00:43:51.510
I have time for questions,
so I'll just

00:43:51.510 --> 00:43:52.990
skip over this lesson.

00:43:52.990 --> 00:43:57.219
Questions, thoughts, ideas?

00:43:57.219 --> 00:43:57.712
Yeah?

00:43:57.712 --> 00:44:02.149
AUDIENCE: So I actually have
a question and a comment.

00:44:02.149 --> 00:44:05.107
So I'll start with the
comment about the

00:44:05.107 --> 00:44:06.340
experiment with the shirts.

00:44:06.340 --> 00:44:06.630
ROBIN ROSENBERG: OK.

00:44:06.630 --> 00:44:07.260
One second.

00:44:07.260 --> 00:44:09.180
Is there a mic they're
supposed to go to?

00:44:09.180 --> 00:44:13.200
Oh, I'm sorry, if you have a
question, just go to a mic.

00:44:13.200 --> 00:44:14.450
Sorry, I forgot about that.

00:44:20.278 --> 00:44:23.150
AUDIENCE: So the comment is
about the experiment with the

00:44:23.150 --> 00:44:25.930
shirts with the Jack Daniels.

00:44:25.930 --> 00:44:27.970
So as you were describing
that, I was thinking to

00:44:27.970 --> 00:44:30.400
myself, well, OK, but what--

00:44:30.400 --> 00:44:32.120
I'll just speak for myself,
but I think

00:44:32.120 --> 00:44:33.460
this is fairly typical.

00:44:33.460 --> 00:44:37.000
What happens is a lot of times
with things like that is

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:39.700
there's a thing that goes on in
your mind where you say--

00:44:39.700 --> 00:44:41.590
not particularly about the Jack
Daniels shirt, that's

00:44:41.590 --> 00:44:42.550
fairly innocuous--

00:44:42.550 --> 00:44:46.130
but somebody wears a particular
shirt and so

00:44:46.130 --> 00:44:49.180
immediately the place you go
to is, well, you made a

00:44:49.180 --> 00:44:51.380
conscious choice to wear
that shirt, right?

00:44:51.380 --> 00:44:55.630
So the wearer is trying to
transmit something about

00:44:55.630 --> 00:44:56.250
themselves.

00:44:56.250 --> 00:44:58.710
Whether that's right or wrong,
it doesn't matter.

00:44:58.710 --> 00:45:01.740
But that's sort of what goes
on in your head as the

00:45:01.740 --> 00:45:04.220
observer is, well, you chose
to wear that shirt.

00:45:04.220 --> 00:45:06.470
You're trying to send out
some kind of signal.

00:45:06.470 --> 00:45:08.240
ROBIN ROSENBERG: Right.

00:45:08.240 --> 00:45:10.140
AUDIENCE: Which could
be totally wrong.

00:45:10.140 --> 00:45:11.600
The other thing is
about superheros.

00:45:11.600 --> 00:45:14.810
So I'm the father of two boys
who are both adults now.

00:45:14.810 --> 00:45:18.910
But the one thing that struck
me-- and I know, I watched, I

00:45:18.910 --> 00:45:20.520
read comic books when
I was a kid.

00:45:20.520 --> 00:45:23.340
And I'm old enough that I
remember the George Reeves

00:45:23.340 --> 00:45:25.990
Superman, although
it was in reruns.

00:45:25.990 --> 00:45:29.030
I'm not quite that old.

00:45:29.030 --> 00:45:32.080
But one thing that struck me
with both of my sons was how

00:45:32.080 --> 00:45:38.180
early the hook sank
about superheroes.

00:45:38.180 --> 00:45:41.140
I mean, I can remember my older
son being like 18 months

00:45:41.140 --> 00:45:45.080
old, taking his baby blanket
and asking us to wrap it

00:45:45.080 --> 00:45:46.780
around his neck as a cape.

00:45:49.600 --> 00:45:52.010
In fact, at this point, I wish
they'd wean themselves from

00:45:52.010 --> 00:45:56.220
that stuff, but maybe
by 40 they will.

00:45:56.220 --> 00:45:56.780
ROBIN ROSENBERG: Or not.

00:45:56.780 --> 00:45:58.310
AUDIENCE: But yeah, maybe not.

00:45:58.310 --> 00:46:02.270
But one thing that struck
me was there's got to be

00:46:02.270 --> 00:46:04.340
something deeper going
on there, right?

00:46:04.340 --> 00:46:09.365
There's something in their
very, very young minds.

00:46:09.365 --> 00:46:09.630
ROBIN ROSENBERG: Primal.

00:46:09.630 --> 00:46:12.040
AUDIENCE: There's something
that's resonating in terms of

00:46:12.040 --> 00:46:13.980
what they desire to be.

00:46:13.980 --> 00:46:16.300
Or I'm not sure exactly what
it is, but that the

00:46:16.300 --> 00:46:17.800
hook sinks so early.

00:46:17.800 --> 00:46:20.380
I mean, obviously there's
a lot more.

00:46:20.380 --> 00:46:22.730
If all your friends are
surrounding you and they're

00:46:22.730 --> 00:46:26.910
all carrying Spiderman lunch
boxes, and there's a lot more

00:46:26.910 --> 00:46:28.760
of that stuff, certainly,
than when I was younger.

00:46:28.760 --> 00:46:31.040
But I'm wondering if there's
something deeper than that,

00:46:31.040 --> 00:46:33.500
that's it's not just media
pressure, that there's some

00:46:33.500 --> 00:46:35.160
hook that sets in very early.

00:46:35.160 --> 00:46:36.340
ROBIN ROSENBERG: Absolutely.

00:46:36.340 --> 00:46:39.870
And actually the book that's
not on sale there, "Our

00:46:39.870 --> 00:46:41.290
Superheroes, Ourselves"
addresses

00:46:41.290 --> 00:46:42.060
some of this question.

00:46:42.060 --> 00:46:45.610
It's essays by psychologists
talking about our relationship

00:46:45.610 --> 00:46:47.770
with superheroes and the ways in
which we're similar to and

00:46:47.770 --> 00:46:50.160
different from superheroes.

00:46:50.160 --> 00:46:53.230
So before there were
superheros, it

00:46:53.230 --> 00:46:55.590
was cowboys and Indians.

00:46:55.590 --> 00:46:58.740
It was probably Sampson
versus Delilah.

00:46:58.740 --> 00:47:02.550
I mean, throughout history
kids play.

00:47:02.550 --> 00:47:07.810
And they play about characters
that they know, Bible figures.

00:47:07.810 --> 00:47:10.380
If they're exposed to
superheroes, it's superheroes.

00:47:10.380 --> 00:47:14.600
Kids really want moral clarity
about right and wrong.

00:47:14.600 --> 00:47:17.690
And I think part of what
superhero stories offer, aside

00:47:17.690 --> 00:47:22.140
from the violent part, is the
kid superhero stories offer

00:47:22.140 --> 00:47:23.650
moral clarity.

00:47:23.650 --> 00:47:26.610
And they also show that
sometimes doing the right

00:47:26.610 --> 00:47:29.550
thing is hard, which is a lesson
that we actually want

00:47:29.550 --> 00:47:31.020
adults to remember.

00:47:31.020 --> 00:47:34.270
So being a whistle-blower is
a great example that's a

00:47:34.270 --> 00:47:37.260
superhero tale without
the power.

00:47:37.260 --> 00:47:40.780
So kids are just gravitated
toward moral

00:47:40.780 --> 00:47:43.370
clarity and also power.

00:47:43.370 --> 00:47:46.440
I mean, kids are unbelievably
powerless in the world.

00:47:46.440 --> 00:47:49.780
They have so little control
over anything.

00:47:49.780 --> 00:47:53.930
And the idea of being this
superhero and having all of

00:47:53.930 --> 00:47:55.450
these powers and being
able to do all

00:47:55.450 --> 00:47:57.350
these things is amazing.

00:47:57.350 --> 00:47:59.880
And then the other piece, just
to address that, is the kids

00:47:59.880 --> 00:48:04.640
are easily self-hypnotizable.

00:48:04.640 --> 00:48:08.100
In the Western world, most
of us lose our ability to

00:48:08.100 --> 00:48:10.090
hypnotize ourselves.

00:48:10.090 --> 00:48:11.670
But kids are amazing at it.

00:48:11.670 --> 00:48:12.990
That's their fantasy play.

00:48:12.990 --> 00:48:14.280
They are there.

00:48:14.280 --> 00:48:17.920
And so superhero stories, when
they imagine them, it is

00:48:17.920 --> 00:48:20.680
incredibly vivid as
if it's real.

00:48:20.680 --> 00:48:25.360
And so when they put on a cape
and imagine themselves flying,

00:48:25.360 --> 00:48:26.910
they are self-hypnotized.

00:48:26.910 --> 00:48:29.140
I mean, they're not going
to jump out a window or

00:48:29.140 --> 00:48:29.880
anything like that.

00:48:29.880 --> 00:48:32.310
Or, unfortunately, occasionally
that happens if

00:48:32.310 --> 00:48:34.750
there aren't screens
on the window.

00:48:34.750 --> 00:48:37.840
But it's very vivid and powerful
for them in a way

00:48:37.840 --> 00:48:41.470
that dream life can be this
amazing release and experience

00:48:41.470 --> 00:48:44.480
that when they imagine being
a superhero, it taps into

00:48:44.480 --> 00:48:45.970
something very primal.

00:48:45.970 --> 00:48:48.530
Before it was superheroes,
it was something else.

00:48:48.530 --> 00:48:51.820
But I think that
urge is there.

00:48:51.820 --> 00:48:53.026
Yeah?

00:48:53.026 --> 00:48:54.800
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:48:54.800 --> 00:48:57.900
So you talked about the
inferences that we

00:48:57.900 --> 00:49:01.330
automatically make based
on the visual

00:49:01.330 --> 00:49:05.190
cues that we observe.

00:49:05.190 --> 00:49:10.140
And I understand that as an
empirical observation.

00:49:10.140 --> 00:49:13.820
You also give the advice that,
be careful what you wear.

00:49:13.820 --> 00:49:15.500
ROBIN ROSENBERG: Yes.

00:49:15.500 --> 00:49:17.700
AUDIENCE: I felt like that was
a little insufficient if you

00:49:17.700 --> 00:49:21.530
don't talk about the
conditioning that is done on

00:49:21.530 --> 00:49:26.410
society and why those inferences
are actually made.

00:49:26.410 --> 00:49:33.490
Because there's nothing about
looking at a character from

00:49:33.490 --> 00:49:38.850
below or looking at a character
from above that is

00:49:38.850 --> 00:49:45.040
any correlation to good or bad,
negative or positive.

00:49:45.040 --> 00:49:47.400
So I was hoping you could
talk a little bit about

00:49:47.400 --> 00:49:48.800
re-conditioning.

00:49:48.800 --> 00:49:49.560
ROBIN ROSENBERG: Sure.

00:49:49.560 --> 00:49:50.050
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:49:50.050 --> 00:49:52.490
ROBIN ROSENBERG: So all
of us have our own

00:49:52.490 --> 00:49:54.660
unique learning history.

00:49:54.660 --> 00:49:56.030
Some of it is shared.

00:49:56.030 --> 00:49:59.020
If we watch the same films and
movies and TVs, or read the

00:49:59.020 --> 00:50:02.880
same books, and are exposed to
things, then part of our

00:50:02.880 --> 00:50:04.190
learning history is shared.

00:50:04.190 --> 00:50:06.870
And part of it is unique to our
family and our community.

00:50:06.870 --> 00:50:08.540
And then our own personal,
unique

00:50:08.540 --> 00:50:10.190
history that no one shares.

00:50:10.190 --> 00:50:17.360
And all of those go into the
assumptions and inferences

00:50:17.360 --> 00:50:19.060
that you make about people.

00:50:19.060 --> 00:50:23.760
So for instance, I have two
sons who work at Google.

00:50:23.760 --> 00:50:26.660
So I feel like I can say this.

00:50:26.660 --> 00:50:30.270
So if you grow up in a
family where people

00:50:30.270 --> 00:50:34.260
don't iron their shirts.

00:50:34.260 --> 00:50:38.560
Your kids will have certain
assumptions that are going to

00:50:38.560 --> 00:50:41.680
be different about people who
wear non-ironed shirts, who

00:50:41.680 --> 00:50:44.490
wear rumpled shirts, than
someone who grows up in a

00:50:44.490 --> 00:50:47.430
family where the underwear
was ironed.

00:50:47.430 --> 00:50:51.520
And so that will influence what
you think when you see

00:50:51.520 --> 00:50:54.140
someone in a rumpled shirt.

00:50:54.140 --> 00:50:58.160
You can absolutely overwrite
what you've

00:50:58.160 --> 00:51:00.170
learned with new learning.

00:51:00.170 --> 00:51:03.630
And so if instead of working
at Google, you now end up

00:51:03.630 --> 00:51:07.060
working on Wall Street, and you
are told in no uncertain

00:51:07.060 --> 00:51:09.700
terms that you need to have
a suit and tie every day.

00:51:09.700 --> 00:51:11.240
And it needs to be really
expensive suit.

00:51:11.240 --> 00:51:14.080
And you should definitely
have ironed shirts.

00:51:14.080 --> 00:51:15.940
You will have new learning.

00:51:15.940 --> 00:51:20.390
And you will learn whatever the
culture there wants you to

00:51:20.390 --> 00:51:24.360
learn about ironed shirts,
about what it means.

00:51:24.360 --> 00:51:28.810
So humans are great learners,
some of the time.

00:51:28.810 --> 00:51:31.790
And so in this context, you
would learn new things.

00:51:31.790 --> 00:51:36.730
If a film came out that shot
the superhero the other way

00:51:36.730 --> 00:51:40.830
around and the villain from
above, and that was the new

00:51:40.830 --> 00:51:44.690
point-of-view style, then we
would just unlearn that.

00:51:44.690 --> 00:51:46.990
This new learning would
overwrite the old learning.

00:51:46.990 --> 00:51:47.980
Did that answer your question?

00:51:47.980 --> 00:51:49.280
AUDIENCE: That wasn't
my question.

00:51:49.280 --> 00:51:51.040
ROBIN ROSENBERG: No, did that
answer your question?

00:51:51.040 --> 00:51:53.420
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:51:53.420 --> 00:51:56.614
ROBIN ROSENBERG:
OK, not really?

00:51:56.614 --> 00:52:02.870
AUDIENCE: So I totally
understand the conditioning of

00:52:02.870 --> 00:52:04.120
inferences.

00:52:05.990 --> 00:52:09.540
But what I was getting at
is I think they are very

00:52:09.540 --> 00:52:10.240
subjective.

00:52:10.240 --> 00:52:20.270
And they sometimes result in
undesirable effects against

00:52:20.270 --> 00:52:20.960
other people.

00:52:20.960 --> 00:52:27.851
So I think there has to be an
effort to recondition those

00:52:27.851 --> 00:52:29.800
factors that cause
the inferences so

00:52:29.800 --> 00:52:33.200
that they, I guess--

00:52:33.200 --> 00:52:34.880
ROBIN ROSENBERG: Ah, OK.

00:52:34.880 --> 00:52:35.080
Right.

00:52:35.080 --> 00:52:38.160
So the effort to recondition
more accurately.

00:52:38.160 --> 00:52:40.800
The problem is it's like
the Will Smith dilemma.

00:52:40.800 --> 00:52:43.100
We can't do that all the time.

00:52:43.100 --> 00:52:46.360
We just can't function in the
world and simultaneously be

00:52:46.360 --> 00:52:48.650
reconditioning ourselves and
checking whether the

00:52:48.650 --> 00:52:51.320
assumptions we're making about
people, is that true.

00:52:51.320 --> 00:52:54.450
We can do it some of the
time, when it counts.

00:52:54.450 --> 00:52:56.100
When we care, we can do it.

00:52:56.100 --> 00:52:58.720
When I'm meeting someone for the
first time and I know if

00:52:58.720 --> 00:53:02.090
I'm looking, and I say, oh,
this person is X, Y, and Z

00:53:02.090 --> 00:53:03.760
based on how they look.

00:53:03.760 --> 00:53:07.830
I can take the time to get
to know that person.

00:53:07.830 --> 00:53:10.190
I can make a decision to take
the time to get to know the

00:53:10.190 --> 00:53:13.660
person to see, are my hypotheses
about them correct?

00:53:13.660 --> 00:53:15.120
But we can't do that
all the time.

00:53:15.120 --> 00:53:18.290
It's just a huge amount
of effort.

00:53:18.290 --> 00:53:20.570
Yeah?

00:53:20.570 --> 00:53:22.920
AUDIENCE: Question about your
specific choice of hero

00:53:22.920 --> 00:53:27.190
exemplar for lesson two,
specifically Batman as an

00:53:27.190 --> 00:53:30.410
example of someone who is
psychologically well adjusted

00:53:30.410 --> 00:53:32.050
to psychological shock.

00:53:32.050 --> 00:53:34.310
ROBIN ROSENBERG: OK.

00:53:34.310 --> 00:53:36.140
Let's put down the
gauntlets here.

00:53:36.140 --> 00:53:38.040
OK, go ahead.

00:53:38.040 --> 00:53:41.210
AUDIENCE: I think especially in
the post-Alan Moore, post

00:53:41.210 --> 00:53:46.280
'80s comic hero era, we have
started looking at superheroes

00:53:46.280 --> 00:53:47.380
who are simply not

00:53:47.380 --> 00:53:48.760
psychologically well put together.

00:53:48.760 --> 00:53:53.890
And Batman, the vigilante who
has serious issues in current

00:53:53.890 --> 00:53:58.245
generation post-rebirth
DC comics, why?

00:53:58.245 --> 00:53:58.970
There are--

00:53:58.970 --> 00:53:59.170
ROBIN ROSENBERG: [INAUDIBLE]

00:53:59.170 --> 00:54:01.650
AUDIENCE: --any number of people
who are better put--

00:54:01.650 --> 00:54:04.480
even Cyclops as fewer issues
than Batman who is

00:54:04.480 --> 00:54:06.360
fundamentally a broken person.

00:54:06.360 --> 00:54:08.930
ROBIN ROSENBERG: OK, so I
don't agree with you.

00:54:08.930 --> 00:54:14.376
I wrote a book called "Whats
the Matter with Batman?"

00:54:14.376 --> 00:54:17.000
AUDIENCE: I will
be buying that.

00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:17.980
ROBIN ROSENBERG: I will
send you a copy.

00:54:17.980 --> 00:54:20.210
Come afterwards.

00:54:20.210 --> 00:54:24.130
And I kind of go through the
likely diagnoses for him.

00:54:24.130 --> 00:54:29.210
And part of where I come out is
that everyone has issues.

00:54:29.210 --> 00:54:32.600
You cannot live in this world
and not have issues.

00:54:32.600 --> 00:54:36.080
His issues are obvious,
granted.

00:54:36.080 --> 00:54:38.796
But I don't think that he's
really screwed up.

00:54:38.796 --> 00:54:43.680
I think that this is a man who
is a serious guy, perhaps by

00:54:43.680 --> 00:54:45.010
temperament, we don't know.

00:54:45.010 --> 00:54:47.390
I mean, it's hard to say what
he was like before.

00:54:47.390 --> 00:54:49.930
I mean, I think "Batman
Begins" film is really

00:54:49.930 --> 00:54:51.470
interesting in how it portrayed

00:54:51.470 --> 00:54:53.570
him how he was before.

00:54:53.570 --> 00:54:55.050
And that's really an
interesting take.

00:54:55.050 --> 00:54:57.330
But he's a serious guy.

00:54:57.330 --> 00:55:00.220
I don't think being serious
means your screwed up.

00:55:00.220 --> 00:55:01.420
It just means you're serious.

00:55:01.420 --> 00:55:03.990
He has issues with
relationships.

00:55:03.990 --> 00:55:05.090
Who doesn't?

00:55:05.090 --> 00:55:09.740
I mean, put aside the 50%
divorce rate, how many

00:55:09.740 --> 00:55:12.050
relationships don't work?

00:55:12.050 --> 00:55:15.670
I mean most intimate
relationships we have in life

00:55:15.670 --> 00:55:17.050
don't work out.

00:55:17.050 --> 00:55:19.310
I'm not going to say he's
screwed up for that reason.

00:55:19.310 --> 00:55:21.500
Then all of us would
be screwed up.

00:55:21.500 --> 00:55:23.980
If you go down the list
of the ways--

00:55:23.980 --> 00:55:27.440
he's serious, and he's
a dedicated guy.

00:55:27.440 --> 00:55:32.130
It's like to say that Navy SEALs
would be screwed up, or

00:55:32.130 --> 00:55:35.100
thoracic surgeons who spend--I
don't know--

00:55:35.100 --> 00:55:39.830
20 years in training and are on
call all the time and often

00:55:39.830 --> 00:55:42.820
have difficult marriages and
lives because they're on call

00:55:42.820 --> 00:55:44.300
all the time and it's
incredibly--

00:55:44.300 --> 00:55:46.430
you have to have a certain
personality to get to be a

00:55:46.430 --> 00:55:50.200
thoracic surgeon, to get
to the end stage.

00:55:50.200 --> 00:55:52.490
It's sort of an occupational
hazard.

00:55:52.490 --> 00:55:55.020
Being a cop changes people.

00:55:55.020 --> 00:55:58.090
Any discipline, any
occupation changes

00:55:58.090 --> 00:55:59.520
people in certain ways.

00:55:59.520 --> 00:56:01.720
So I would take issue
with you about that.

00:56:01.720 --> 00:56:03.120
And I was intentional.

00:56:03.120 --> 00:56:03.760
AUDIENCE: I appreciate that.

00:56:03.760 --> 00:56:04.850
ROBIN ROSENBERG: OK.

00:56:04.850 --> 00:56:06.630
But give me your address.

00:56:06.630 --> 00:56:08.570
I'll send you a copy
of the book.

00:56:08.570 --> 00:56:11.740
Any other questions?

00:56:11.740 --> 00:56:13.370
No more people want
to take on Batman?

00:56:13.370 --> 00:56:13.960
I'm ready.

00:56:13.960 --> 00:56:15.970
I'm prepared.

00:56:15.970 --> 00:56:17.250
Anything else?

00:56:17.250 --> 00:56:20.337
Oh, yeah?

00:56:20.337 --> 00:56:21.220
AUDIENCE: It's sort of a

00:56:21.220 --> 00:56:24.180
follow-up to the last question.

00:56:24.180 --> 00:56:25.840
Then where did the dark
age come from?

00:56:25.840 --> 00:56:28.770
I mean we had in the '30s and
the '40s, we had the golden

00:56:28.770 --> 00:56:32.350
age, which was these really
naive characters, and the '50s

00:56:32.350 --> 00:56:33.560
in the '60s.

00:56:33.560 --> 00:56:36.490
In the '60s and '70s, they got
a little more serious.

00:56:36.490 --> 00:56:41.510
And then with "Watchmen" and
"The Dark Knight Returns," all

00:56:41.510 --> 00:56:47.920
of a sudden, they were all, if
not broken, then a whole lot

00:56:47.920 --> 00:56:51.710
less pure and a whole lot
harder to root for.

00:56:51.710 --> 00:56:54.800
Some of that, I think, just came
from the changes in how

00:56:54.800 --> 00:56:57.410
comic books got sold
in the 1980s.

00:56:57.410 --> 00:57:01.300
But that was a long time ago.

00:57:01.300 --> 00:57:04.100
And we had a dark Superman
movie this

00:57:04.100 --> 00:57:05.685
year, or so I've told.

00:57:05.685 --> 00:57:09.580
Where does the attraction with
dark superheroes come from?

00:57:09.580 --> 00:57:12.720
I mean, light superheros,
I understand.

00:57:12.720 --> 00:57:15.650
Have we grown up?

00:57:15.650 --> 00:57:17.170
ROBIN ROSENBERG: I actually
think part of it is that we

00:57:17.170 --> 00:57:18.290
have grown up.

00:57:18.290 --> 00:57:21.800
So those of us who read comics
as kids, or Saturday morning

00:57:21.800 --> 00:57:23.530
cartoons, we grew up.

00:57:23.530 --> 00:57:26.800
And those simple moral tales
that appealed to us as kids do

00:57:26.800 --> 00:57:28.490
not appeal to us now.

00:57:28.490 --> 00:57:30.610
They were simplistic.

00:57:30.610 --> 00:57:36.220
And they are not consistent with
our nuanced experience of

00:57:36.220 --> 00:57:41.130
the world where morality is
often relative and it depends

00:57:41.130 --> 00:57:42.690
on context.

00:57:42.690 --> 00:57:48.840
And so I think that Alan Moore
unleashed the pent-up desire

00:57:48.840 --> 00:57:51.470
for more sophisticated
stories.

00:57:51.470 --> 00:57:55.450
And then I think with that, we
started wondering, so what

00:57:55.450 --> 00:57:57.940
would it be like to
be a superhero?

00:57:57.940 --> 00:57:59.930
What would it be like
to be Batman?

00:57:59.930 --> 00:58:04.070
Or Superman is actually a harder
one, but what would it

00:58:04.070 --> 00:58:07.250
be to live day in, day
out as a superhero?

00:58:07.250 --> 00:58:09.600
And we want to see
our characters

00:58:09.600 --> 00:58:11.350
suffer a little bit.

00:58:11.350 --> 00:58:16.190
So if it gets darker, it's
because they get real.

00:58:16.190 --> 00:58:17.700
AUDIENCE: But why did our
generation change?

00:58:17.700 --> 00:58:21.380
Because my mom bought "Action"
number one and regretted the

00:58:21.380 --> 00:58:23.540
rest of her life
not keeping it.

00:58:23.540 --> 00:58:26.650
So she grew up on the really
simplistic superheros.

00:58:26.650 --> 00:58:28.890
And then she grew up.

00:58:28.890 --> 00:58:32.930
Did she just ignore all the
comic book superheroes?

00:58:32.930 --> 00:58:38.430
Or did something happen with
this generation that wanted

00:58:38.430 --> 00:58:40.530
darker superheros that didn't
happen with the previous

00:58:40.530 --> 00:58:45.370
generation that was happy to
have the more pure ones?

00:58:45.370 --> 00:58:46.960
ROBIN ROSENBERG: I think
two things happened.

00:58:46.960 --> 00:58:49.620
One is realism in general.

00:58:49.620 --> 00:58:53.170
Psychological realism was
just in all other

00:58:53.170 --> 00:58:54.645
genres, so why no.

00:58:54.645 --> 00:58:56.340
I mean, even in spaghetti

00:58:56.340 --> 00:58:58.590
Westerns, it started happening.

00:58:58.590 --> 00:59:01.610
Clint Eastwood became
a three-dimensional

00:59:01.610 --> 00:59:03.530
character in his films.

00:59:03.530 --> 00:59:07.470
So I think it was in the
zeitgeist at the time.

00:59:07.470 --> 00:59:16.350
And I also think that for your
mom, maybe you went with your

00:59:16.350 --> 00:59:21.900
mom to see the first Chris
Reeves' "Superman" film?

00:59:21.900 --> 00:59:24.570
Maybe it was a family
affair, maybe not.

00:59:24.570 --> 00:59:26.387
AUDIENCE: She watched "Star
Trek" with me, which fits me a

00:59:26.387 --> 00:59:26.560
little bit better.

00:59:26.560 --> 00:59:28.100
ROBIN ROSENBERG: OK, she
watched "Star Trek."

00:59:28.100 --> 00:59:29.140
AUDIENCE: Almost superheroes.

00:59:29.140 --> 00:59:29.460
ROBIN ROSENBERG: Right.

00:59:29.460 --> 00:59:32.410
But I think we also delayed
having kids.

00:59:32.410 --> 00:59:34.570
And so we were happy to have

00:59:34.570 --> 00:59:38.040
adult-oriented superhero stories.

00:59:38.040 --> 00:59:40.990
Where when people had
kids sooner, it

00:59:40.990 --> 00:59:43.070
was a family affair.

00:59:43.070 --> 00:59:44.740
Reading comics together,
talking about and

00:59:44.740 --> 00:59:45.860
watching the TV shows.

00:59:45.860 --> 00:59:50.400
And so I think it was a more
private experience.

00:59:50.400 --> 00:59:51.550
And that's what was offered.

00:59:51.550 --> 00:59:53.910
And honestly, I think we
just all became more

00:59:53.910 --> 00:59:56.425
psychologically sophisticated
and wanted our

00:59:56.425 --> 00:59:57.613
heroes to be, too.

00:59:57.613 --> 00:59:58.570
AUDIENCE: OK, thank you.

00:59:58.570 --> 00:59:59.820
ROBIN ROSENBERG: A great
question, though.

00:59:59.820 --> 01:00:00.795
And any other questions?

01:00:00.795 --> 01:00:01.060
Yes?

01:00:01.060 --> 01:00:03.486
AUDIENCE: Isn't it the case of
